devil with your clamour! I don't Want you to
speak. Miss Linton, I shall enjoy myself re-
markably in thinking your father will be miser-
able; I shall not sleep for satisfaction. You could
have hit on no surer way of fixing your resi-
dence under my roof, for the next twenty-four
hours, than informing me that such an event
would follow. As to your promise to marry
Linton; I'll take care you shall keep it, for
you shall not quit the place till it is fulfilled."

"Send Ellen then, to let papa know I'm
safe!" exclaimed Catherine, weeping bitterly.
"Or marry me now. Poor papa! Ellen, he'll
think we're lost. What shall we do?"

"Not he! He'll think you are tired of wait-
ing on him, and run off, for a little amuse-
ment," answered Heathcliff. "You cannot
deny that you entered my house of your own
accord, in contempt of his injunctions to the
contrary. And it is quite natural that you
should desire amusement at your age; and that
you should weary of nursing a sick man, and
